bioghist.head: Biographical/Historical note
bioghist.p: Francis Oliver Holmes (1899-1990), phytopathologist. Born in Cambridge, Massachusetts on 26 November 1899 to Fannie Elizabeth Greenleaf Holmes and Frank William Holmes. Raised in Cambridge, Holmes graduated from Rindge Technical High School in 1916 and from the Massachusetts Institute of Technology in June 1921 as one of their few graduates in biological sciences. Holmes pursued graduate work at Johns Hopkins University. There he met his future wife, L. Ruth Deem (1898-1982). They were married in 1924 and their one son, Francis William Holmes, was born in 1929.

Having studied under Robert W. Hegner at Johns Hopkins, Holmes was awarded a doctorate in science in 1924 based on his research thesis, "Herpetomonad Flagellates in Milkweed in the United States." The previous year, Holmes accepted the position of protozoologist at the Boyce Thompson Institute for Plant Research in Yonkers, NY. At the Institute, he worked in close association with Dr. Louis Otto Kunkel who was studying yellows viruses.

In 1932, when Dr. Kunkel was asked to develop a plant virology laboratory for the new Plant and Animal Pathology Department of the Rockefeller Institute for Medical Research, he brought Holmes with him to Princeton, NJ. Holmes remained at the Rockefeller until his retirement in 1965.

During his career, Holmes was noted for his early discovery (1929) of a way to determine the relative concentration of plant virus particles, known as "local lesion assays." He was world-renowned for his long advocacy of the use of Latin binomials to name viruses, culminating in two editions of his book, Handbook of Phytopathogenic Viruses in 1939. This volume was expanded in 1948 under the title, The Filterable Viruses to include non-phytopathogenic viruses. Dr. Holmes developed tobacco-mosaic-virus disease resistant varieties in several crops, including tobacco, tomatoes, and sweet peppers. He served as an officer in the Northeast Division of the American Phytopathological Society. Shortly after his retirement, Holmes was the first recipient of the society's highest honor, the Ruth Allen Award. During his retirement years, Dr. Holmes taught virology for one year at the University of New Hampshire and one year at the University of Illinois.

In his sixty years of scientific research, Dr. Holmes listed 181 publications. Of these, sixty-one were published in the journal, Phytopathology, mostly before his retirement, and 49 more were published in Gleanings in Bee Culture, mostly after his retirement. The remaining 71 are found in 36 other journals or books.

During 1944, 1946, 1948, 1958, and 1959, Holmes and his wife were guests of the Puerto Rico Agricultural Experiment Station in Rio Pedras where he studied the papaya "bunchy-top" disease. In 1961-1962, while a consultant in virology for the United Nations Food and Agricultural Organization, Holmes went to the Guinobatan Agricultural Experiment Station in the Philippine Republic. Here he discovered that the fatal "cadang-cadang" disease of coconut palms did not occur wherever the trees were kept in weed-free surroundings. Thus insect vectors could be suppressed by eliminating certain environmental factors. Also under the auspices of the FAO, Holmes investigated related diseases at an Experiment Station in Kerala Province in southwestern India.

In his retirement years, Dr. Holmes lived in Henniker, New Hampshire, raising bees and studying the taxonomy of willows (Salix). Having first raised bees as a hobby while in New Jersey, once retired, Holmes published many articles about honey, bee life patterns, and nectar secretion of their food plants. Willow pollen is the earliest spring source of food for many bee colonies. Holmes gathered more than one hundred species of Salix on his farm and often donated to botanical gardens the species that they lacked.

Francis Oliver Holmes was struck by a vehicle while walking near his home in Henniker the evening of 12 October 1990, and died on the way to the hospital. He had lived 90 years and 10 1/2 months and is buried with his wife, Ruth, in the Henniker Cemetery.

relatedmaterial.head: Related Materials
relatedmaterial.p: Twelve additional storage cartons of Holmes material exist (Boxes 7-18) which were received by RAC post-1988. All additional materials are closed to scholarly research pending further processing.
See FA803 Francis O. Holmes papers, Rockefeller University Faculty (Ingested by RAC post-1988).
